  "event_preview": "Texas Motor Speedway is a 1.5-mile (2.414 km) quad-oval in Fort Worth, Texas, opened in 1997 with 20-degree banking in Turns 1 and 2 and 24-degree banking in Turns 3 and 4. The SpeedyCash.com 250 is the seventh race of the 2026 NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series season, run over 172 laps (258 miles) with stage breaks at laps 40 and 80. It is the first time the series races on 15-inch tires at a track of one mile or more in 2026, with inner liners used as standard on the Goodyear compounds — the same setup carried over from previous years but untested by teams this season on this type of surface.\n\nKyle Busch enters in Spire Motorsports' No. 7 for his third Truck Series start of 2026, seeking his seventh career win at Texas — which would stand alone as the all-time record at the track. His 2024 victory here came by 0.112 seconds after leading a dominant stretch of laps. Carson Hocevar pulls double duty in the No. 77 Spire entry, fresh off his first career Cup Series victory the previous weekend at Talladega. Christopher Bell, who won the most recent Truck Series event at Bristol, is absent from the entry list this week; 35 trucks are entered for 36 available positions, meaning the entire field will make the race.\n\nThe all-time Truck Series qualifying record at Texas belongs to Nick Sanchez, who turned a 29.219-second lap (184.811 mph) to claim pole for the 2024 SpeedyCash.com 250. The fastest race lap on record in the series at the track belongs to Corey Heim, who clocked a 29.78-second best lap during his 2025 victory at the venue.",
